\section{Writing system}

Danetian orthography makes the language look just like any other European
language. The writing system uses the 26 letters of the standard Latin
alphabet, along with the accute accent (\lan{áéíóúý}) and a couple of
digraphs.

Most letters in the Danetian alphabet represent a single sound. The table
below sumarizes the names of every letter, and the phonemic value.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{c|cc}
	\toprule
	letter & name & sound \\
	\midrule
	a & \lan{a} & \ipa{/a/} \\
	b & \lan{be} & \ipa{/b/} \\
	c & \lan{ce} & \ipa{/k/} \\
	d & \lan{de} & \ipa{/d/} \\
	e & \lan{e} & \ipa{/e/} \\
	f & \lan{ef} & \ipa{/f/} \\
	g & \lan{ge} & \ipa{/g/} \\
	h & \lan{hasj} & \ipa{/x/} \\
	i & \lan{i} & \ipa{/i/} \\
	j & \lan{ja} & \ipa{/j/} \\
	k & \lan{ka} & \ipa{/k/} \\
	l & \lan{el} & \ipa{/l/} \\
	m & \lan{em} & \ipa{/m/} \\
	n & \lan{en} & \ipa{/n/} \\
	o & \lan{o} & \ipa{/o/} \\
	p & \lan{pe} & \ipa{/p/} \\
	q & \lan{qu} & \ipa{/k/} \\
	r & \lan{er} & \ipa{/r/} \\
	s & \lan{es} & \ipa{/s/} \\
	t & \lan{te} & \ipa{/t/} \\
	u & \lan{u} & \ipa{/u/} \\
	v & \lan{ve} & \ipa{/v/} \\
	w & \lan{dublevé} & \ipa{/v/} \\
	x & \lan{ix} & \ipa{/s/, /ks/} \\
	y & \lan{igrek} & \ipa{/i/, /j/} \\
	z & \lan{zed} & \ipa{/z/} \\
	\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

The letter \ipa{⟨c⟩} always sounds like a hard \ipa{/k/}, and
is never palatalized as it is in other European languages. The letter
\ipa{⟨x⟩} sounds like /ʃ/ at the beginning of a word (usually Greek or Spanish
loanwords).
The letter \ipa{⟨y⟩} can take on a vocalic or consonantal value, depending on
context, but it's very intuitive to figure out which one is the case.

The native digraphs used are the following:
\begin{itemize}
	\item \ipa{⟨cj⟩}: \ipa{/tʃ/}
	\item \ipa{⟨gj⟩}: \ipa{/dʒ/}
	\item \ipa{⟨nj⟩}: \ipa{/ɲ/}
	\item \ipa{⟨sj⟩}: \ipa{/ʃ/}
\end{itemize}

In addition to these native digraphs, Danetian also has Greco-Roman digraphs:
\begin{itemize}
	\item \ipa{⟨ch⟩}: \ipa{/x/}
	\item \ipa{⟨ph⟩}: \ipa{/f/}
	\item \ipa{⟨th⟩}: \ipa{/t/}
\end{itemize}

Moreover, if any extraneous Greek consonant cluster appears in the
beginning of a word and cannot be pronounced, such as
\ipa{⟨pt⟩}, \ipa{⟨pn⟩}, \ipa{⟨ps⟩}, or any of the like,
then the first consonant is assumed to be silent. Examples:
\begin{itemize}
	\item \lan{psycha} \ipa{/'si.xa/} \qt{soul}
	\item \lan{pneumonia} \ipa{/new.mo'ni.a/} \qt{pneumonia}
	\item \lan{Ptolemaios} \ipa{/to.le'ma.jos/} \qt{Ptolemy}
\end{itemize}



\section{Stress}

Danetian has a stress accent, much like Modern Greek, Spanish, and Russian.
Every word has exactly one stressed syllable, pronounced stronger than the
rest. By the nature of the language, the stressed syllable is restricted to be
either
\begin{itemize}
	\item the last syllable, in which case the word is called oxytone; or
	\item the penultimate syllable, in which case the word is called
		paroxytone; or finally
	\item the antepenultimate syllable, in which case the word is called
		proparoxytone.
\end{itemize}

In most words, the stress falls as further back as it can. For example, in
\lan{respublica}, \qt{republic}, the \lan{-pu-} is stressed; but in
\lan{respublicamos}, \qt{of the republics}, the \lan{-bli-} is stressed,
because that's as far back as the stress can fall.

In writing, the stress is marked by an acute accent, as in
\lan{natúra} \ipa{[na'tu.ɾa]} \qt{nature},
or it can simply be inferred, as in
\lan{anapreseti} \ipa{[a.na'prɛ.ze.ti]} \qt{he prays}. In order to determine
which words should be marked and which ones should be unmarked, we lay down the
following rules:
\begin{enumerate}
	\item In an unmarked word that ends in a vowel, or a vowel plus
		\lan{-m}, \lan{-n}, \lan{-s}, or \lan{-t}, the stress falls
		on the antepenultimate orthographic
		\textit{vowel} (not syllable) if it can,
		or as far back as possible if the word is shorter.
		\subitem \lan{viros} \ipa{/'vi.ros/} \qt{man}
		\subitem \lan{bena} \ipa{/'be.na/} \qt{woman}
		\subitem \lan{donom} \ipa{/'do.nom} \qt{gift}
		\subitem \lan{praman} \ipa{/'pra.man/} \qt{beginning}
		\subitem \lan{vepti} \ipa{/'vep.ti} \qt{he speaks}
		\subitem \lan{ministeriom} \ipa{/mi.nis'te.rjom/} \qt{ministry}
		\subitem \lan{Mercurios} \ipa{/mer'ku.rjos/} \qt{Mercury}
		\subitem \lan{Demetrios} \ipa{/de'me.trjos/} \qt{Dmitri}
	\item Unmarked words that end in \lan{-ia} constitute an exception to
		the previous rule. In these words, the stress falls on the
		\lan{i}.
		\subitem \lan{Anastasia} \ipa{/a.nas.ta'si.a/} \qt{Anastasia}
		\subitem \lan{vidia} \ipa{/vi'di.a/} \qt{wisdom}
		\subitem \lan{rodia} \ipa{/ro'di.a/} \qt{law}
	\item If an unmarked word ends in a consonant other than
		\lan{-m}, \lan{-n}, \lan{-s}, or \lan{-t}, then the stress
		falls on the last syllable.
		\subitem \lan{Daniel} \ipa{/da'njel/} \qt{Daniel}
		\subitem \lan{Gabriel} \ipa{/ga'brjel/} \qt{Gabriel}
		\subitem \lan{Sadok} \ipa{/sa'dok/} \qt{Zadok} (Biblical name)
		\subitem \lan{Achaz} \ipa{/a'xaz/} \qt{Ahaz} (Biblical name)
	\item In an unmarked word, if these previous rules result in the
		a hiatus after the stressed vowel or possibly including it,
		then the stress is moved to the vowel immediately following.
		\subitem \lan{Joanna} \ipa{/jo'a.na/} \qt{John}
		\subitem \lan{Andrea} \ipa{/an'dre.a/} \qt{Andrew}
\end{enumerate}




\chapter{Nominal morphology}

\section{General properties}

Nouns inflect according to the following categories:
\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{gender:} masculine, feminine, neuter
	\item \textbf{number:} singular, plural
	\item \textbf{case:}
		nominative,
		accusative,
		genitive,
		ablative,
		dative,
		locative,
		instrumental,
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Gender}

Gender is a grammatical property inherent to each noun. Sometimes it's
correlated with biological sex:
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \lan{viros} (\M): man
	\item \lan{bena} (\F): woman
	\item \lan{hertogos} (\M): duke
	\item \lan{hertoga} (\F): duchess
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

Most of the time, however, it has nothing to do with sex:
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \lan{abol} (\M): apple
	\item \lan{anfros} (\M): rain
	\item \lan{barda} (\F): beard
	\item \lan{nas} (\F): nose
	\item \lan{imperiom} (\N): empire
	\item \lan{dranom} (\N): grain
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

\subsection{Number}

Nouns inflect according to number. If a noun refers to a single entity, it's
called \textit{singular}. If it refers to more than one entity, it's called
\textit{plural}.

\subsection{Case}

Nouns can also inflect according to case. Case refers to the grammatical role
that a noun plays in a phrase or sentence. For instance, consider the following
two sentences:

\begin{exe}
	\ex
	\gll
	\lan{Svon}
	\lan{smerdeti}
	\lan{virom}.
	\\
	Dog-{\Nom} bites man-{\Acc}. \\
	\glt The dog bites the man.
\end{exe}

\begin{exe}
	\ex
	\gll
	\lan{Viros}
	\lan{smerdeti}
	\lan{svonam}.
	\\
	Man-{\Nom} bites dog-{\Acc}. \\
	\glt The man bites the dog.
\end{exe}

Clearly, the word for \qt{man} plays a different role in each sentence. In the
first example, the man is receiving the action. In the second one, he is
performing the action. This difference is marked in the different endings:
\lan{viros} when the man performs the action, \lan{virom} when the man receives
the action.

There are seven cases in Danetian. They are listed below, along with their most
common functions.
\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{nominative:} Refers to the subject of a sentence. This is
		the standard form of a noun.
		\begin{exe}
			\ex
			\textbf{\lan{Viros}}
			\lan{lufjeti}
			\lan{svonam.}
			\\
			Man-{\Nom} loves dog-{\Acc}.
			\glt The \textbf{man} loves the dog.
		\end{exe}

	\item \textbf{accusative:} Refers to the direct object of a sentence.
		\begin{exe}
			\ex
			\lan{Svon}
			\lan{lufjeti}
			\textbf{\lan{virom}}.
			\\
			Dog-{\Nom} loves man-{\Acc}
			\glt The dog loves the \textbf{man}.
		\end{exe}
	\item \textbf{genitive:} Denotes possession. Equivalent to the
		phrase \qt{of + [something]}.
		\begin{exe}
			\ex
			\lan{Mjanka}
			\textbf{\lan{virosjo}}
			\lan{lufjeti}
			\lan{svonam}.
			\\
			Kitten-{\Nom} man-{\Gen} loves dog-{\Acc}.
			\glt The \textbf{man's} kitten loves the dog.
		\end{exe}
	\item \textbf{ablative:} Can refer to a source of something, or denote
		movement away from something. Equivalent to the phrase
		\qt{from + [something]}.
		\begin{exe}
			\ex
			\lan{Mjanka}
			\lan{peperet}
			\lan{apo}
			\textbf{\lan{virad}}
			\lan{svonei}.
			\\
			Kitten-{\Nom} ran from man-{\Abl} dog-{\Dat}.
			\glt The kitten ran \textbf{from the man} to the dog.
		\end{exe}
	\item \textbf{dative:} Can refer to the indirect object of a sentence,
		or denote movement towards something. Equivalent to the phrase
		\qt{to + [something]}.
		\begin{exe}
			\ex
			\lan{Svon}
			\lan{dedót}
			\lan{fastom}
			\textbf{\lan{viroi}}.
			\\
			Dog-{\Nom} gave stick-{\Acc} man-{\Dat}.
			\glt The dog gave the stick \textbf{to the man}.
		\end{exe}
	\item \textbf{locative:} Refers to a location. Roughly equivalent to the
		phrase \qt{in + [location]}.
		\begin{exe}
			\ex
			\lan{Mjanka}
			\lan{sedjeto}
			\lan{ana}
			\textbf{\lan{viri}}.
			\\
			Kitten-{\Nom} was-sitting on man-{\Loc}.
			\glt The kitten was sitting \textbf{on the man}.
		\end{exe}
	\item \textbf{instrumental:} Can denote a tool or instrument with which
		an action is performed, or can refer to an entity that gives
		company to another. Equivalent to the phrase
		\qt{with + [something]}.
		\begin{exe}
			\ex
			\lan{Svon}
			\lan{igret}
			\lan{som}
			\textbf{\lan{vire}}.
			\\
			Dog-{\Nom} was-playing with man-{\Ins}.
			\glt The dog was playing \textbf{with the man}.
		\end{exe}
\end{itemize}


\section{Strong and weak cases}

The seven cases can be divided into two types: the strong cases ({\Nom} and
\Acc), and the weak cases (\Gen, \Abl, \Dat, \Loc, and \Ins). There are two
main reasons for this.
\begin{enumerate}[i]
	\item For neuter nouns, the strong cases are always identical, while
		for all other nouns, the strong cases are always distinct.
		Thus, it makes sense to group the strong cases together. For
		example,

		\begin{center}
		\begin{tabular}{llll}
			\toprule
			~ & gift (\N) & man (\M) & woman (\F) \\
			\midrule
			\Nom & \lan{donom} & \lan{viros} & \lan{bena} \\
			\Acc & \lan{donom} & \lan{virom} & \lan{benam} \\
			\bottomrule
		\end{tabular}
		\end{center}

	\item There are some nouns that use one stem for the strong cases, and
		a different stem for the weak cases:

		\begin{center}
		\begin{tabular}{llll}
			\toprule
			~ & thought & dog & lake \\
			\midrule
			\Nom & \lan{mentis} & \lan{svon} & \lan{lokus} \\
			\Gen & \lan{manties} & \lan{sunes} & \lan{alkves} \\
			\bottomrule
		\end{tabular}
		\end{center}
\end{enumerate}


\section{Inflection classes}
By examining how each noun inflects, we can come up with several broad
categories:
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{I}: \lan{a}-stem nouns
	\item \textbf{II}: \lan{o}-stem nouns
	\item \textbf{III-i}: \lan{i}-stem nouns
	\item \textbf{III-u}: \lan{u}-stem nouns
	\item \textbf{III-s}: \lan{es}-stem nouns
	\item \textbf{III-n}: \lan{en}-stem nouns
	\item \textbf{III-L}: liquid-stem nouns
	\item \textbf{III-F}: fleeting \lan{s} nouns
	\item \textbf{III-C}: consonant-stem nouns
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

Historically, these categories have been grouped into the \textit{first
declension} (\textbf{I}), \textit{second declension} (\textbf{II}), and
\textit{third declension} (\textbf{III}). As can be seen from the list above,
the third declension contains many subcategories.

\subsection{\lan{a}-stem nouns}

Another of the biggest classes of nouns are the \lan{a}-stems. The vast
majority of these are feminine, but there are some masculines here and there.
Some familiar examples include:
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \lan{barda} (\F): beard
	\item \lan{bena} (\F): woman
	\item \lan{danva} (\F): tongue; language
	\item \lan{lana} (\F): wool
	\item \lan{luksna} (\F): moon
	\item \lan{redia} (\F): law, right
