\subsection{Liquid-stem nouns}

The liquid consonants are \lan{l} and \lan{r}. If the {\Nom-\Sg} of a noun ends
in a liquid consonant, then it belongs to the class of liquid-stem nouns. This
class includes both masculine and feminine nouns. Some familiar examples are:
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \lan{abol}\footnotemark[\value{footnote}] (\M): apple
	\item \lan{bor}\footnotemark[\value{footnote}] (\M): thief
	\item \lan{brater} (\M): brother
	\item \lan{denator, danatres} (\M): parent
	\item \lan{dotor, datres} (\M): giver
	\item \lan{fugater, fugtres} (\F): daughter
	\item \lan{for, fures} (\M): door
	\item \lan{mater} (\F): mother
	\item \lan{pater} (\M): father
	\item \lan{sper, aspres} (\M): sparrow
	\item \lan{ster, astres} (\M): star
	\item \lan{svesor}\footnotemark[\value{footnote}] (\F): sister
	\item \lan{vistor} (\M): witness
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

