\subsection{Simple cardinals beyond twenty}
\label{sec:simple-cardinals-beyond-twenty}

Every simple cardinal 20 and above inflects like any Danetian noun. They're
all inherently plural, so the noun phrase that they govern must also be in the
plural. However, they may not necessarily agree in case; the case agreement
rules are discussed in section \ref{sec:case-agreement-for-simple-cardinals}.
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \lan{vidsant} (\Num): twenty
	\item \lan{tridsont} (\Num): thirty
	\item \lan{petvardsont} (\Num): forty
	\item \lan{pempedsont} (\Num): fifty
	\item \lan{svedsont} (\Num): sixty
	\item \lan{septandsont} (\Num): seventy
	\item \lan{oktodsont} (\Num): eighty
	\item \lan{nevandsont} (\Num): ninety
	\item \lan{satón} (\Num): hundred
	\item \lan{tusontis} (\Num): thousand
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

The simple cardinals between 20 and 90 inflect like a consonantal-stem
noun, with the caveat that they're always in the singular.
The numerals \lan{satón} and \lan{tusontis} inflect like a consonantal-stem and
\lan{i}-stem noun, respectively, and they can be either singular or plural.

\section{Case agreement for simple cardinals}
\label{sec:case-agreement-for-simple-cardinals}

As we saw in sections \ref{sec:one} and \ref{sec:two-three-and-four}, the
cardinals 1-4 must agree with the gender, number, and case of the noun phrase
that they govern. Of course, the numerals 2-4 are inherently plural, so the
noun phrase must be cast into the plural.

However, the simple cardinals greater than or equal to 5 follow a slightly
more complicated set of rules:
\begin{enumerate}[i]
	\item The case of the cardinal determines the case of the entire
		numeral phrase.
	\item If we wish to inflect the numeral phrase into one of the
		strong cases ({\Nom} and {\Acc}), then the noun phrase
		must be inflected in the genitive plural.

		\begin{exe}
			\ex
			\gll
			\lan{pempe}
			\lan{viróm}
			\lan{i}
			\lan{benóm} \\
			five-{\Nom} men-{\Gen}-{\Pl} and women-{\Gen}-{\Pl} \\
			\glt \qt{five men and women}
		\end{exe}

		\begin{exe}
			\ex
			\gll
			\lan{tusontim}
			\lan{dranóm}
			\lan{sales} \\
			thousand-{\Acc} grains-{\Gen}-{\Pl}
			of-salt-{\Gen}-{\Sg} \\
			\glt \qt{one thousand grains of salt}
		\end{exe}

	\item If we wish to inflect the numeral phrase into one of the weak
		cases ({\Gen}, {\Abl}, {\Dat}, {\Loc}, {\Ins}), then the noun
		phrase also agrees with that case.

		\begin{exe}
			\ex
			\gll
			\lan{som}
			\lan{petvardsonte}
			\lan{virois} \\
			with forty-{\Ins} men-{\Ins}-{\Pl} \\
			\glt with the forty men
		\end{exe}

		\begin{exe}
			\ex
			\gll
			\lan{apo}
			\lan{oktomos}
			\lan{stadimos} \\
			from eight-{\Abl} locations-{\Abl}-{\Pl} \\
			\glt from eight locations
		\end{exe}
\end{enumerate}

A brief table should illustrate these simple rules.

