\chapter{Verbal Morphology}

\section{General properties}

Verbs inflect according to the following categories:
\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{person}: first, second, third
	\item \textbf{number}: singular, plural
	\item \textbf{mood}: indicative, subjunctive, imperative
	\item \textbf{voice}: active, mediopassive
	\item \textbf{aspect}: perfective, imperfective
\end{itemize}

The starting point for analyzing the morphology of Danetian verbs is the
stem. The different endings appended at the end of the
verb stem mark the different
inflections of the verb. If the endings are appended directly after a
consonant, as in \lan{vepti}, then the verb is called \textit{athematic}. But
if an intervening vowel is placed between the stem and the ending, as in
\lan{vopeti}, then the verb is called \textit{thematic}.

In the dictionary, verbs are placed in the active indicative present third
person singular, continuing the tradition of Proto-Indo-European.

\section{Thematic verbs}
\label{sec:thematic-verbs}

Thematic verbs are divided into three inflectional
classes for convenience: T1, T2, and T3.

