\chapter{General syntax}

\section{Copula omission}
\label{sec:copula-omission}

The copula can be optionally omitted if it is in the present tense.

\begin{exe}
	\ex
	\gll
	\lan{Aicaterína}
	\lan{en}
	\lan{Gallí}. \\
	Catherine in France-{\Loc} \\
	\glt Catherine is in France.
\end{exe}

\begin{exe}
	\ex
	\gll
	\lan{Petros}
	\lan{mechaniskos}
	\lan{insjenier}. \\
	Peter mechanical engineer \\
	\glt Peter is a mechanical engineer.
\end{exe}

\begin{exe}
	\ex
	\gll
	\lan{Nestor}
	\lan{i}
	\lan{Antonios}
	\lan{physicoi}. \\
	Nestor and Anthony physicists \\
	\glt Nestor and Anthony are physicists.
\end{exe}

\begin{exe}
	\ex
	\gll
	\lan{Benjamín}
	\lan{viros}
	\lan{de}
	\lan{Alexandra}
	\lan{bena}. \\
	Benjamin man and Alexandra woman \\
	\glt Benjamin is a man, and Alexandra is a woman.
\end{exe}

If it's not in the present tense, then the copula can still be omitted,
provided that it was used in the previous sentence. This way,
the tense of the omitted copula is inferred from the copula in the previous
sentence.

\begin{exe}
	\ex
	\gll
	\lan{En}
	\lan{prameni}
	\lan{but}
	\lan{Verdom},
	\lan{da}
	\lan{Verdom}
	\lan{opi}
	\lan{Divosjo},
	\lan{da}
	\lan{Divos}
	\lan{Verdom}. \\
	in beginning-{\Loc} was word and word next-to God-{\Gen} and
	God word \\
	\glt In the beginning was the Word, and the Word was with God, and the
	Word was God.
\end{exe}

\section{Possession}

Unlike most European languages, Danetian does not typically use a verb
\textit{to have} to express possession. Rather, it uses a grammatical
construction: Possessor-{\Dat} copula object-{\Nom}.

\begin{exe}
	\ex
	\gll
	\lan{Medjo}
	\lan{iti}
	\lan{sonts}
	\lan{rufros}
	\lan{automobilis}. \\
	me-{\Dat} it-goes being-{\M} red-{\M} automobile-{\M} \\
	\glt I will have a red car.
\end{exe}

\begin{exe}
	\ex
	\gll
	\lan{Petroi}
	\lan{i}
	\lan{Nestorei}
	\lan{esti}
	\lan{bibliom}
	\lan{physicas}. \\
	Peter-{\Dat} and Nestor-{\Dat} is book physics-{\Gen}. \\
	\glt Peter and Nestor have a physics book.
\end{exe}

\begin{exe}
	\ex
	\gll
	\lan{Aicaterínai}
	\lan{bunt}
	\lan{tres}
	\lan{bles}. \\
	Catherine-{\Dat} had three apples \\
	\glt Catherine had three apples.
\end{exe}

Of course, the copula can be omitted according to the
rules in section \ref{sec:copula-omission}.

\chapter{Time expressions}

\section{Hours and minutes}

\section{Days of the week}

The days of the week are the following:
\begin{itemize}
	\item \lan{din Soles} (\M): Sunday
	\item \lan{din Lunas} (\M): Monday
	\item \lan{din Marties} (\M): Tuesday
	\item \lan{din Mercuriosjo} (\M): Wednesday
	\item \lan{din Jovies} (\M): Thursday
	\item \lan{din Venesos} (\M): Friday
	\item \lan{din Saturnosjo} (\M): Saturday
\end{itemize}

In order to express that an event occured on one of the days of the week,
the dative case is used.
\begin{exe}
	\ex
	\gll
	\lan{Imi}
	\lan{enam}
	\lan{vidonts}
	\lan{dinei}
	\lan{Saturnosjo}. \\
	I-will-go her-{\Acc} seeing-{\M} day-{\Dat} Saturn-{\Gen} \\
	\glt I will see her on Saturday.
\end{exe}

When saying that an event will happen \textit{this week}, or
\textit{that week}, or \textit{next week}, or any
similar phrase, we use the construction \lan{ana} + accusative. A rough
equivalent in English would be to say \textit{upon this week}, for instance.
\begin{exe}
	\ex
	\gll
	\lan{Vojasj}
	\lan{pepramenjet}
	\lan{ana}
	\lan{probanvesam}
	\lan{soliskam}. \\
	Trip started on past-{\Acc} week-{\Acc} \\
	\glt The trip started last week.
\end{exe}

\section{Days of the month}

When saying that something will happen \textit{on that day}, or on any
particular numeric day of the month, we use the genitive case.
\begin{exe}
	\ex
	\gll
	\lan{Urusj}
	\lan{anandjóto}
	\lan{tosjo}
	\lan{memorabilies}
	\lan{dines}. \\
	War concluded that-{\Gen} memorable-{\Gen} day-{\Gen} \\
	\glt The war ended on that memorable day.
\end{exe}
\begin{exe}
	\ex
	\gll
	\lan{Vi}
	\lan{dedamímeda}
	\lan{oktamosjo}
	\lan{juniosjo}. \\
	We were-married eighth-{\Acc} June-{\Acc} \\
	\glt We got married on the eight of June.
\end{exe}

\section{Months and years}

Below is a list of all twelve months of the Western calendar.
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \lan{januarios} (\M): January
	\item \lan{februarios} (\M): February
	\item \lan{martios} (\M): March
	\item \lan{aprilis} (\M): April
	\item \lan{majos} (\M): May
	\item \lan{junios} (\M): June
	\item \lan{julios} (\M): July
	\item \lan{augustos} (\M): August
	\item \lan{september} (\M): September
	\item \lan{october} (\M): October
	\item \lan{november} (\M): November
	\item \lan{december} (\M): December
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

When saying that something will happen on a particular month or year, we use
the construction \lan{en} + locative. Years are expressed with cardinal
numbers.
\begin{exe}
	\ex
	\gll
	\lan{Dedenáto}
	\lan{en}
	\lan{tusonti}
	\lan{nevani}
	\lan{satonisu}
	\lan{nevandsonti}
	\lan{nevani}. \\
	I-was-born in thousand-{\Loc} nine-{\Loc} hundreds-{\Loc} ninety-{\Loc}
	nine-{\Loc} \\
	\glt I was born in 1999.
\end{exe}
\begin{exe}
	\ex
	\gll
	\lan{Schola}
	\lan{pramenjeti}
	\lan{en}
	\lan{septembri}. \\
	School-{\Nom} starts in September-{\Loc} \\
	\glt School starts in September.
\end{exe}

